  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity aimed at disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate. Virtually all countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often as part of broader efforts to fight financial crime, terrorism financing, and organized crime.\n\nKey international frameworks, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT) measures. Countries that are members of the FATF or follow its recommendations have implemented legal frameworks to criminalize money laundering, require financial institutions to monitor and report suspicious transactions, and cooperate internationally to combat these activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely and consistently regarded as illegal across jurisdictions worldwide.",
